The purpose of an SQL INNER JOIN clause is to combine rows from two or more tables based on a related column between them. It creates a new result set containing rows where the value of the joining column is present in both tables. For example, consider a Users table with columns UserID (primary key) and Username, and a Posts table with columns PostID, PostContent, and AuthorID (a foreign key referencing Users.UserID). To retrieve a list of all posts along with the username of the author who wrote them, you would use an INNER JOIN. The query would be:
SELECT Posts.PostContent, Users.Username FROM Posts INNER JOIN Users ON Posts.AuthorID = Users.UserID;
This query links the two tables using the shared author/user ID, combining the post content with the corresponding author's username for each post.

The purpose of a linear regression model is to find and model the linear relationship between a dependent variable (the value you want to predict) and one or more independent variables (the predictors). It aims to fit a straight line to the data that minimises the distance between the line and the actual data points. This line can then be used to predict a continuous numeric value for new data.

